			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">I'm interested in hearing them as well.  I expect they will either be baseline or body, since Mythic probably feels they've enhanced Mind enough.  
<br />

<br />
After playing a few nights, I have noticed that even the second highest mez immune does have a noticeable effect.  Mez doesn't last nearly as long.  In some cases, that permits me to get an AOE mez off I wouldn't otherwise have been able to do.  Problem is that with all the purges and resists, I'm still likely to be the first in the group dead.   On rare occasions it will save my purge, or help me if purge is already gone.  
<br />

<br />
The power regen does very little for me (I already had mcl II and serenity II).  However, I do notice that now everyone is demanding it be cast on them all the time (why only a 10 minute timer?).  Likely it IS useful for helping to keep the cleric in mana, but a minstrel has a way less annoying means to accomplish this end.  I guess  I wouldn't want to give it up, but there is a serious tradeoff here in terms of benefit vs. annoyance factor.  I'm sure it's VERY nice for PvE though.
<br />

<br />
Charming all Mobs is nice, since it's a bit less annoying to get one now.  However, I'm finding that I tend to actually live longer without a pet in RVR because it's harder to identify me as the sorc without one, at least when traveling in groups of 8 or more.  I'll have to try this more both with and without a pet and decide whether the pet is more of an advantage or a liability.  Also, I haven't played in emain since the patch.  I'm assuming casting pets are still extremely rare and hard to find there, if they exist at all, and those are far and away the most useful pets for RVR.  Tank pets are too easy to run away from, and with bladeturn and such, by the time the actually do anything to an opponent, I'm likely to be dead.  That would not be true if we could run away, but in most cases if I try to run I'm snared/rooted/stunned/mezzed/debuffed long enough for a tank to catch me. 
<br />

<br />
Summary:  Although the patch has a couple noticeable effects for RVR,  the advantages for a mind spec sorc in RVR are slight, and most of the previous complaints about mind sorcs for RVR remain valid after the patch.  Because they die so quickly in RVR and get no RPs for the main ability they bring to the table, they usually get only a fraction of the RPs gotten by the rest of the group.  Most flavor of the month sorcs may find this truth very discouraging once they get to real RVR.  I don't anticipate that many more mind sorcs lasting there for very long.  I expect that most who don't quit outright or revert to their main will respec to body, particularly with the increased area of the lower mez, and will still likely do better in RVR than the mind sorc, if for no other reason than that they will have a much better chance of killing non-mezzable opponents before dying themselves.  If they improve the body line, it's game over.  
<br />

<br />

<br />
Workarounds:  Some of the things that might help in the absence of direct help from Mythic are:
<br />

<br />
Hps Hps Hps.  Get as many as you can.  Demand both con buffs, and get as many as you can on items/armor.  The idea is to stay alive long enough for the cleric to notice you are in trouble and do something about it.  If you are one-shotted, there's nothing he could have done.  
<br />

<br />
Don't go anywhere without a good cleric.  It's pretty much a waste of time <img src="images/smiles/icon_wink.gif" alt="icon_wink.gif" border="0" />.  A GOOD cleric who keeps you targeted unless healing someone else has a fair chance of keeping you alive in most situations.  If you stick close to your smite cleric, he might be able to stun the toons incoming to you and give you a chance to run or lay a mez or AOE root over them.  You can also CC the toons that try to disrupt your cleric to keep him healing...a fine tradeoff.  
<br />

<br />
Hang to the back of your group.  You are most likely to die if multiple people target you, but many tanks can survive this.  The best strategy I've found is to let the opponents pick targets who are not you, and THEN step forward to CC them.  Even if the result of that is to tie down anyone who isn't otherwise engaged, that can be a huge benefit.  If your group is really good, they might avoid hitting a mezzed target they've already engaged and assist someone else.  That takes an exceptional group though, don't expect it in a pickup group.
<br />

<br />
Move move move.  The easiest way to get targeted is by standing still, and that also allows alot of additional styles and such to be used against you, particularly by steathers.  If you aren't casting, you should be moving.  
<br />

<br />
Hope this helps.
<br />

<br />
Tequitus</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
